<font color="#FF0000">UP CLOSE AND PERSONAL</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec  5 15:12:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gary<br>
Great post, As much as I was scared, and feared much in Nam, I feared fear the most, of not being there for someone else. Unable to disassociate from the incoming fire because of personal fear was one thing. Disassociation from the incoming action in order to survive and help others was altogether different.<br><br>
Once or twice if a Marine respond under fire, next time they were left behind, in the rear with the gear. <br>
Some weren't ever taken into battle because they were dead scared.<br><br>
It was those that wanted to prove themselves who like your good friend was tough until the real stuff started flying that often made me angry, but just as often, I was there to help them out. Risked my neck many times for them, even when they weren't firing. But it wasn't until someone was killed or wounded because of their inaction, that they never went back out into the bush, those were our rules and because of that we survived. <br><br>
Your post was well appreciated. A couple of times some just got tired of it all and walked off the field, didn't we all think of doing that often. But our honor, trust, friendship and believe in each other kept us engaged and firing. <br><br>
Once a person responded in combat and engaged the enemy, all else and anything else he may had done was forgiven. He had won the right of passage into that honorable position we call warriors. <br><br>
I was always, always scared until the first round was fired, then it was all training, stimulus response, they shoot at me I shoot back, I've done this before. Some earned my highest respect because they played dead at the foot of the enemy, the gooks took their weapons and they played dead. <br><br>
I wouldn't been able to do that, Marine Corps training, &quot;you don't give up your weapon&quot; they did, played dead and the gooks took their weapons and afterwards they felt bad, as if they had let everyone down, because they had allowed the enemy to take their weapons, while they were still alive. But they instead had our deepest respect. <br><br>
As Chief said to one Marine who had frozen the first time in combat, after he told Chief his fire team leader, &quot;I pissed all over myself, and I was too scared to fire back.&quot; Chief answered him, &quot;at least your alive.&quot;<br>
Next time that grunt was up there, up front and personal.<br><br>
OD, Green you touched a lot of memories today, thank you.<br>
Cook<br>

